[{"sha":"8fd47e61015b658fa5150fb89d936bf7184ba8df","author":{"name":"Ben Barsdell","email":"fb55efc015c19b6b983311e9fae7c0ecda2e4774@nvidia.com"},"message":"Use vectorized load/store in GatherOpKernel

- Vectorized load/store achieves higher memory throughput.
- This commit chooses the optimal vector size that is compatible with
  the data shape and pointer alignment.
- Note that the ldg function would require more changes to support the
  vectorized types, but it is not actually needed: the use of 'const
  __restrict__' means the kernel still generates LDG instructions
  without it.
- Some quick benchmarking showed the following speedups with this commit
  when gathering vectors of length 256 on an NVIDIA TITAN V GPU:
    float64: 1.02x
    float32: 1.07x
    float16: 1.35x
    bool:    1.67x","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/8fd47e61015b658fa5150fb89d936bf7184ba8df"},{"sha":"4360a1b1da63dd38f635e2d7ce8066ddb12002a7","author":{"name":"Ben Barsdell","email":"fb55efc015c19b6b983311e9fae7c0ecda2e4774@nvidia.com"},"message":"Fix alignment_of(T*) to return elements not bytes","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/4360a1b1da63dd38f635e2d7ce8066ddb12002a7"},{"sha":"80ee15562599e4042675705936ccc24db2e74e9d","author":{"name":"Ben Barsdell","email":"fb55efc015c19b6b983311e9fae7c0ecda2e4774@nvidia.com"},"message":"Fix AlignedVector uniform value constructor

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Fold tfl.reshape into tfl.fully_connected

tfl.fully_connected supports keep_num_dims = true so if we have a tfl.reshape
after a tfl.fully_connected what restores the same batch dimensions folded by
the tfl.fully_connected then it can be folded.

We do this transformation at the beginning of the tfl optimise pattern list to
ensure that these reshapes are folded into the fully connected op instead of
being sinked past other (primarily elementwise) ops.

[{"sha":"e96ae7913a2534f836a92b4a1aebf403a31d6b8a","author":{"name":"Katherine Wu","email":"3597b8ab71b66d46ec439caf0c075cd0b82fcc57@google.com"},"message":"Export StructuredCoder as an internal API.

StructuredCoder is the only thing that decodes the input signatures from the SavedModel concrete functions, and Keras uses it to build the layers loaded from config. The layers must be built before loading the other functions/objects from the SavedModel in order to prevent them from creating new sublayers (which would not have the correct weights). Thus, we can't remove the use of StructuredCoder from Keras right now.

[{"sha":"b31c2073f058ee979e2085473ffff274f82eeefd","author":{"name":"Dimitris Vardoulakis","email":"532a0f5dcb324b87a62941a290161c72e1fa9537@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:HLO] Cleanly destruct fusion instructions and their computations.

If a fusion instruction dies before its computation, the computation becomes unreachable, but it may not be destructed until later. In this case, we need to clear its back-pointer to the fusion instruction, otherwise it will point to freed memory. Similarly, when a fusion computation dies, we must clear the fusion instructions's called_computations_.

We also add a boolean field in HloComputation to determine if it is a fusion computation, since with this CL we can have (unreachable) fusion computations whose fusion instruction is null.

Last, do a nullptr check during module cloning, to avoid runtime errors due to unreachable computations.

Previously, when using custom kernel creators the function library runtime being
passed to the custom `CreateKernel` call was the wrong one (different from
other `CreateKernel` call) which led to missing func def's in following
scenario:
1) Custom kernel creator is used.
2) `FunctionLibraryRuntimeImpl::CreateKernel` is called directly from
   `FunctionLibraryRuntimeImpl::CreateItem`.
3) The `item` uses a function library runtime overlay which contains func def's
   that are missing from `this`.

    the cluster.

    that it won't compile again

[{"sha":"8fd47e61015b658fa5150fb89d936bf7184ba8df","author":{"name":"Ben Barsdell","email":"fb55efc015c19b6b983311e9fae7c0ecda2e4774@nvidia.com"},"message":"Use vectorized load/store in GatherOpKernel

- Vectorized load/store achieves higher memory throughput.
- This commit chooses the optimal vector size that is compatible with
  the data shape and pointer alignment.
- Note that the ldg function would require more changes to support the
  vectorized types, but it is not actually needed: the use of 'const
  __restrict__' means the kernel still generates LDG instructions
  without it.
- Some quick benchmarking showed the following speedups with this commit
  when gathering vectors of length 256 on an NVIDIA TITAN V GPU:
    float64: 1.02x
    float32: 1.07x
    float16: 1.35x
    bool:    1.67x","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/8fd47e61015b658fa5150fb89d936bf7184ba8df"},{"sha":"4360a1b1da63dd38f635e2d7ce8066ddb12002a7","author":{"name":"Ben Barsdell","email":"fb55efc015c19b6b983311e9fae7c0ecda2e4774@nvidia.com"},"message":"Fix alignment_of(T*) to return elements not bytes","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/4360a1b1da63dd38f635e2d7ce8066ddb12002a7"},{"sha":"80ee15562599e4042675705936ccc24db2e74e9d","author":{"name":"Ben Barsdell","email":"fb55efc015c19b6b983311e9fae7c0ecda2e4774@nvidia.com"},"message":"Fix AlignedVector uniform value constructor

  vectorized types, but it is not actually needed: the use of 'const

  without it.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Fold tfl.reshape into tfl.fully_connected

tfl.fully_connected supports keep_num_dims = true so if we have a tfl.reshape
after a tfl.fully_connected what restores the same batch dimensions folded by
the tfl.fully_connected then it can be folded.

We do this transformation at the beginning of the tfl optimise pattern list to
ensure that these reshapes are folded into the fully connected op instead of
being sinked past other (primarily elementwise) ops.

Previously, when using custom kernel creators the function library runtime being
passed to the custom `CreateKernel` call was the wrong one (different from
other `CreateKernel` call) which led to missing func def's in following
scenario:
1) Custom kernel creator is used.
2) `FunctionLibraryRuntimeImpl::CreateKernel` is called directly from
   `FunctionLibraryRuntimeImpl::CreateItem`.
3) The `item` uses a function library runtime overlay which contains func def's
   that are missing from `this`.

StructuredCoder is the only thing that decodes the input signatures from the SavedModel concrete functions, and Keras uses it to build the layers loaded from config. The layers must be built before loading the other functions/objects from the SavedModel in order to prevent them from creating new sublayers (which would not have the correct weights). Thus, we can't remove the use of StructuredCoder from Keras right now.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363540007
Change-Id: I0cd72666013e9b8696aa26052ca6fde57e15f8fc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/d7d893b1af5307d2fe196a8796216ffb81578287"},{"sha":"b31c2073f058ee979e2085473ffff274f82eeefd","author":{"name":"Dimitris Vardoulakis","email":"532a0f5dcb324b87a62941a290161c72e1fa9537@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:HLO] Cleanly destruct fusion instructions and their computations.

If a fusion instruction dies before its computation, the computation becomes unreachable, but it may not be destructed until later. In this case, we need to clear its back-pointer to the fusion instruction, otherwise it will point to freed memory. Similarly, when a fusion computation dies, we must clear the fusion instructions's called_computations_.

We also add a boolean field in HloComputation to determine if it is a fusion computation, since with this CL we can have (unreachable) fusion computations whose fusion instruction is null.

Last, do a nullptr check during module cloning, to avoid runtime errors due to unreachable computations.

- This commit chooses the optimal vector size that is compatible with
  the data shape and pointer alignment.
- Note that the ldg function would require more changes to support the
  vectorized types, but it is not actually needed: the use of 'const
  __restrict__' means the kernel still generates LDG instructions
  without it.
- Some quick benchmarking showed the following speedups with this commit
  when gathering vectors of length 256 on an NVIDIA TITAN V GPU:

  vectorized types, but it is not actually needed: the use of 'const
  __restrict__' means the kernel still generates LDG instructions

This commit integrates all SVG icons that have been drawn to date, by Pete Whelpton and Eirik Bakke.

These icons have all been drawn according to the style guide on https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/NETBEANS-2617 , which aims to maintain the same general look as the old NetBeans icons, with some modernizations. The goal is for the new SVG icons to look OK next to the old bitmap icons (since there will always be bitmap icons in the mix for the foreseeable future).

* Install SVG icons in the online documentation popup, and in ETable and TreeTableView's column selection button.
* Copy the 'Back' and 'Forward' SVG icons to various places that all used the same bitmap or a similar-looking bitmap of the same dimensions.
* Add 'Arrow Up' and 'Arrow Right' SVG icons in the same style as the left/right icons previously committed. Use these two icons in all locations that have a similar-looking bitmap icon of the same size (16x16).
* Add Pete Whelpton's SVG icons, donated with his permission. All duplicate locations identified.
* Add an SVG 'Refresh' icon, and copy it into all the places that were previously using a similar-looking icon of the same dimensions.
* Added an SVG version of the magnifying glass dropdown button in quicksearch (used in two locations), as well as 'Zoom In' and 'Zoom Out' icons based on the same shape, used in several places.
* Added an SVG version of the 15x14 'Find' icon (magnifying glass shape) to all relevant locations.
* Added an SVG version of the 16x16 'Find' icon (magnifying glass shape, slightly larger) to all relevant locations. (Both 15x14 and 16x16 versions existed of the same magnifying glass motif; I've made SVG versions at both sizes to guarantee backwards-compatibility.)
* Added an SVG 'database' icon, and copied it into every icon location that uses this motif (hard drive spindle cylinder shape).
* Added an SVG 'warning' icon, and copied it into every icon location that uses the same motif at the same size (exclamation mark on yellow triangle).
* Added SVG versions of 'plus' and 'minus' icons.
* Added an SVG version of 'hierarchy.png' (expandable tree nodes motif).
* Added an SVG version of the 'Print' icon.
* Added an SVG version of the 'Original Size' icon (used in the image viewer).
* Add a 'Closed Folder' SVG icon, and copy it into all locations where this kind of motif is currently used. In the LAF module, add the SVG file as a separate prefix which will be referenced in SVG support code to be added later.
* Add an 'Open Folder' SVG icon, and copy it into all locations where this kind of motif is currently used. In the LAF module, add the SVG file as a separate prefix which will be referenced in SVG support code to be added later.

- Vectorized load/store achieves higher memory throughput.
- This commit chooses the optimal vector size that is compatible with
  the data shape and pointer alignment.
- Note that the ldg function would require more changes to support the
  vectorized types, but it is not actually needed: the use of 'const
  __restrict__' means the kernel still generates LDG instructions
  without it.
- Some quick benchmarking showed the following speedups with this commit
  when gathering vectors of length 256 on an NVIDIA TITAN V GPU:
    float64: 1.02x
    float32: 1.07x
    float16: 1.35x
    bool:    1.67x","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/8fd47e61015b658fa5150fb89d936bf7184ba8df"},{"sha":"4360a1b1da63dd38f635e2d7ce8066ddb12002a7","author":{"name":"Ben Barsdell","email":"fb55efc015c19b6b983311e9fae7c0ecda2e4774@nvidia.com"},"message":"Fix alignment_of(T*) to return elements not bytes","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/4360a1b1da63dd38f635e2d7ce8066ddb12002a7"},{"sha":"80ee15562599e4042675705936ccc24db2e74e9d","author":{"name":"Ben Barsdell","email":"fb55efc015c19b6b983311e9fae7c0ecda2e4774@nvidia.com"},"message":"Fix AlignedVector uniform value constructor

- This is cleaner and allows other kernels to use DispatchToVectorized

    1) don't compile a cluster the very first time it is executed.
    skip until threshold is reached. This makes it symmetrical to
    subsequent compilations of the cluster.
    2) bump the threshold for compilation to the third execution of
    the cluster.
    3) change megamorphic flagging to incldue compiel time. If a cluster
    ever takes more than 30 seconds to compile, mark it megamorphic so
    that it won't compile again

Asynchronous compilation
    1) add option to opt into asynchronous compilation
    2) asynchronous compilation uses a dedicated number of threads
    to start a cluster instance compilation while the fallback path
    is executed
    3) limit number of ongoing compilations to a fixed threshold

change some VLOG levels to make level 2 less verbose","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/6b09fcc93d6bd0e1afe943362ab9a0b1a8549cb5"}]

- Vectorized load/store achieves higher memory throughput.
- This commit chooses the optimal vector size that is compatible with
  the data shape and pointer alignment.
- Note that the ldg function would require more changes to support the
  vectorized types, but it is not actually needed: the use of 'const
  __restrict__' means the kernel still generates LDG instructions
  without it.
- Some quick benchmarking showed the following speedups with this commit
  when gathering vectors of length 256 on an NVIDIA TITAN V GPU:
    float64: 1.02x
    float32: 1.07x
    float16: 1.35x

    1) don't compile a cluster the very first time it is executed.
    skip until threshold is reached. This makes it symmetrical to
    subsequent compilations of the cluster.
    2) bump the threshold for compilation to the third execution of
    the cluster.
    3) change megamorphic flagging to incldue compiel time. If a cluster
    ever takes more than 30 seconds to compile, mark it megamorphic so
    that it won't compile again

Asynchronous compilation
    1) add option to opt into asynchronous compilation
    2) asynchronous compilation uses a dedicated number of threads
    to start a cluster instance compilation while the fallback path
    is executed
    3) limit number of ongoing compilations to a fixed threshold

  the data shape and pointer alignment.

  vectorized types, but it is not actually needed: the use of 'const
  __restrict__' means the kernel still generates LDG instructions
  without it.

    1) don't compile a cluster the very first time it is executed.
    skip until threshold is reached. This makes it symmetrical to
    subsequent compilations of the cluster.
    2) bump the threshold for compilation to the third execution of
    the cluster.
    3) change megamorphic flagging to incldue compiel time. If a cluster
    ever takes more than 30 seconds to compile, mark it megamorphic so
    that it won't compile again

    1) add option to opt into asynchronous compilation
    2) asynchronous compilation uses a dedicated number of threads
    to start a cluster instance compilation while the fallback path
    is executed
    3) limit number of ongoing compilations to a fixed threshold

* Move traversal logic to ReactFiberCommitWork

The current traversal logic is spread between ReactFiberWorkLoop and
ReactFiberCommitWork, and it's a bit awkward, especially when
refactoring. Idk the ideal module structure, so for now I'd rather keep
it all in one file.

* Traverse commit phase effects iteratively

We suspect that using the JS stack to traverse through the tree in the
commit phase is slower than traversing iteratively.

I've kept the recursive implementation behind a flag, both so we have
the option to run an experiment comparing the two, and so we can revert
it easily later if needed.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Axighi/react/commits/25b18d31c8b7ffd256416672dc21c50dd22ac3dc"},{"sha":"779a472b0901b2d28e382f3850b2ad09a555b014","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Prevent inlining into recursive commit functions (#20105)

Adds a bunch of no-inline directives to commit phase functions to
prevent them from being inlined into one of our recursive algorithms.

The motivation is to minimize the number of variables in the recursive
functions, since each one contributes to the size of the stack frame.

Theoretically, this could help the performance of both the recursive
and non-recursive (iterative) implementations of the commit phase,
since even the iterative implementation sometimes uses the JS stack.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Axighi/react/commits/779a472b0901b2d28e382f3850b2ad09a555b014"},{"sha":"b6a750be3ca0fc4126ef018e205c951b890c1881","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Make DevTools Websocket retry delay configurable (#20107)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Axighi/react/commits/b6a750be3ca0fc4126ef018e205c951b890c1881"},{"sha":"343d7a4a7eb621a31ba946309b557e0988be3a63","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Fast Refresh: Don't block DevTools commit hook (#20129)

In some scenarios (either timing dependent, or pre-FR compatible React versions) FR blocked calling the React DevTools commit hook. This PR adds a test and a fix for that.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Axighi/react/commits/343d7a4a7eb621a31ba946309b557e0988be3a63"},{"sha":"ffd84233568fd9d277eaba7c01d53d516f6f132f","author":{"name":"Sebastian Markbåge","email":"8a279ae1320350359ecfec7a379763633f1edc4c@fb.com"},"message":"[Flight] Add support for Module References in transport protocol (#20121)

* Refactor Flight to require a module reference to be brand checked

This exposes a host environment (bundler) specific hook to check if an
object is a module reference. This will be used so that they can be passed
directly into Flight without needing additional wrapper objects.

* Emit module references as a special type of value

We already have JSON and errors as special types of "rows". This encodes
module references as a special type of row value. This was always the
intention because it allows those values to be emitted first in the stream
so that as a large models stream down, we can start preloading as early
as possible.

We preload the module when they resolve but we lazily require them as they
are referenced.

* Emit module references where ever they occur

This emits module references where ever they occur. In blocks or even
directly in elements.

* Don't special case the root row

I originally did this so that a simple stream is also just plain JSON.

However, since we might want to emit things like modules before the root
module in the stream, this gets unnecessarily complicated. We could add
this back as a special case if it's the first byte written but meh.

* Update the protocol

* Add test for using a module reference as a client component

* Relax element type check

Since Flight now accepts a module reference as returned by any bundler
system, depending on the renderer running. We need to drastically relax
the check to include all of them. We can add more as we discover them.

* Move flow annotation

Seems like our compiler is not happy with stripping this.

* Some bookkeeping bug

* Can't use the private field to check","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Axighi/react/commits/ffd84233568fd9d277eaba7c01d53d516f6f132f"}]

[{"sha":"6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane (#20681)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/DerrickCN/react/commits/6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439"},{"sha":"97fce318a6618bc883a8578f58b9083484c9e6d7","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@gmail.com"},"message":"Experiment: Infer the current event priority from the native event (#20748)

* Warn if static flag is accidentally cleared

"Static" fiber flags are flags that are meant to exist for the lifetime
of a component. It's really important not to accidentally reset these,
because we use them to decide whether or not to perform some operation
on a tree (which we can do because they get bubbled via `subtreeFlags)`.

We've had several bugs that were caused by this mistake, so we actually
don't rely on static flags anywhere, yet. But we'd like to.

So let's roll out this warning and see if it fires anywhere. Once we
can confirm that there are no warnings, we can assume that it's safe
to start using static flags.

I did not wrap it behind a feature flag, because it's dev-only, and we
can use our internal warning filter to hide this from the console.

* Intentionally clear static flag to test warning

* ...and fix it again","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/DerrickCN/react/commits/696e736be11b22e8d4fa40438d235b63db7fddde"}]

[{"sha":"e31086320ea0305e2cc70490160ee30480471680","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Remove cli test for duplicate --net/--network opts

This seems to be testing a strange case, specifically that one can set
the `--net` and `--network` in the same command with the same network.

Indeed this used to work with older CLIs but newer ones error out when
validating the request before sending it to the daemon.

Opening this for discussion because:

1. This doesn't seem to be testing anything at all related to the rest
   of the test
2. Not really providing any value here.
3. Is testing that a technically invalid option is successful (whether
   the option should be valid as it relates to the CLI accepting it is
   debatable).
4. Such a case seems fringe and even a bug in whatever is calling the
   CLI with such options.

  the data shape and pointer alignment.

  vectorized types, but it is not actually needed: the use of 'const

Change-Id: I914714d034291661a9efa6b14d6f3941200e5a04","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/27447895fcef704f8134a5c72735941d39e89ba6"},{"sha":"0bb0d612563802e9c4c36e1c310c92ba2224154f","author":{"name":"Michael Gester","email":"83d127f0cbc4af4bb827dac2517a3f01bb4703b7@google.com"},"message":"Fix missing func def's when using custom kernel creators

Previously, when using custom kernel creators the function library runtime being
passed to the custom `CreateKernel` call was the wrong one (different from
other `CreateKernel` call) which led to missing func def's in following
scenario:
1) Custom kernel creator is used.
2) `FunctionLibraryRuntimeImpl::CreateKernel` is called directly from
   `FunctionLibraryRuntimeImpl::CreateItem`.
3) The `item` uses a function library runtime overlay which contains func def's
   that are missing from `this`.

Change-Id: Ie3c19a336a453f9bfde06f78c082364679d19c99","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/0bb0d612563802e9c4c36e1c310c92ba2224154f"},{"sha":"e96ae7913a2534f836a92b4a1aebf403a31d6b8a","author":{"name":"Katherine Wu","email":"3597b8ab71b66d46ec439caf0c075cd0b82fcc57@google.com"},"message":"Export StructuredCoder as an internal API.

StructuredCoder is the only thing that decodes the input signatures from the SavedModel concrete functions, and Keras uses it to build the layers loaded from config. The layers must be built before loading the other functions/objects from the SavedModel in order to prevent them from creating new sublayers (which would not have the correct weights). Thus, we can't remove the use of StructuredCoder from Keras right now.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363540007
Change-Id: I0cd72666013e9b8696aa26052ca6fde57e15f8fc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/d7d893b1af5307d2fe196a8796216ffb81578287"},{"sha":"b31c2073f058ee979e2085473ffff274f82eeefd","author":{"name":"Dimitris Vardoulakis","email":"532a0f5dcb324b87a62941a290161c72e1fa9537@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:HLO] Cleanly destruct fusion instructions and their computations.

If a fusion instruction dies before its computation, the computation becomes unreachable, but it may not be destructed until later. In this case, we need to clear its back-pointer to the fusion instruction, otherwise it will point to freed memory. Similarly, when a fusion computation dies, we must clear the fusion instructions's called_computations_.

We also add a boolean field in HloComputation to determine if it is a fusion computation, since with this CL we can have (unreachable) fusion computations whose fusion instruction is null.

Last, do a nullptr check during module cloning, to avoid runtime errors due to unreachable computations.

   that are missing from `this`.

Change-Id: Ie3c19a336a453f9bfde06f78c082364679d19c99","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/0bb0d612563802e9c4c36e1c310c92ba2224154f"},{"sha":"e96ae7913a2534f836a92b4a1aebf403a31d6b8a","author":{"name":"Katherine Wu","email":"3597b8ab71b66d46ec439caf0c075cd0b82fcc57@google.com"},"message":"Export StructuredCoder as an internal API.

StructuredCoder is the only thing that decodes the input signatures from the SavedModel concrete functions, and Keras uses it to build the layers loaded from config. The layers must be built before loading the other functions/objects from the SavedModel in order to prevent them from creating new sublayers (which would not have the correct weights). Thus, we can't remove the use of StructuredCoder from Keras right now.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363540007
Change-Id: I0cd72666013e9b8696aa26052ca6fde57e15f8fc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/d7d893b1af5307d2fe196a8796216ffb81578287"},{"sha":"b31c2073f058ee979e2085473ffff274f82eeefd","author":{"name":"Dimitris Vardoulakis","email":"532a0f5dcb324b87a62941a290161c72e1fa9537@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:HLO] Cleanly destruct fusion instructions and their computations.

If a fusion instruction dies before its computation, the computation becomes unreachable, but it may not be destructed until later. In this case, we need to clear its back-pointer to the fusion instruction, otherwise it will point to freed memory. Similarly, when a fusion computation dies, we must clear the fusion instructions's called_computations_.

We also add a boolean field in HloComputation to determine if it is a fusion computation, since with this CL we can have (unreachable) fusion computations whose fusion instruction is null.

Last, do a nullptr check during module cloning, to avoid runtime errors due to unreachable computations.

Change-Id: I914714d034291661a9efa6b14d6f3941200e5a04","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/PowerOlive/tensorflow/commits/27447895fcef704f8134a5c72735941d39e89ba6"},{"sha":"0bb0d612563802e9c4c36e1c310c92ba2224154f","author":{"name":"Michael Gester","email":"83d127f0cbc4af4bb827dac2517a3f01bb4703b7@google.com"},"message":"Fix missing func def's when using custom kernel creators

Previously, when using custom kernel creators the function library runtime being
passed to the custom `CreateKernel` call was the wrong one (different from
other `CreateKernel` call) which led to missing func def's in following
scenario:
1) Custom kernel creator is used.
2) `FunctionLibraryRuntimeImpl::CreateKernel` is called directly from
   `FunctionLibraryRuntimeImpl::CreateItem`.
3) The `item` uses a function library runtime overlay which contains func def's
   that are missing from `this`.

Change-Id: Ie3c19a336a453f9bfde06f78c082364679d19c99","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/PowerOlive/tensorflow/commits/0bb0d612563802e9c4c36e1c310c92ba2224154f"},{"sha":"e96ae7913a2534f836a92b4a1aebf403a31d6b8a","author":{"name":"Katherine Wu","email":"3597b8ab71b66d46ec439caf0c075cd0b82fcc57@google.com"},"message":"Export StructuredCoder as an internal API.

StructuredCoder is the only thing that decodes the input signatures from the SavedModel concrete functions, and Keras uses it to build the layers loaded from config. The layers must be built before loading the other functions/objects from the SavedModel in order to prevent them from creating new sublayers (which would not have the correct weights). Thus, we can't remove the use of StructuredCoder from Keras right now.

Change-Id: I0cd72666013e9b8696aa26052ca6fde57e15f8fc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/PowerOlive/tensorflow/commits/d7d893b1af5307d2fe196a8796216ffb81578287"},{"sha":"b31c2073f058ee979e2085473ffff274f82eeefd","author":{"name":"Dimitris Vardoulakis","email":"532a0f5dcb324b87a62941a290161c72e1fa9537@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:HLO] Cleanly destruct fusion instructions and their computations.

If a fusion instruction dies before its computation, the computation becomes unreachable, but it may not be destructed until later. In this case, we need to clear its back-pointer to the fusion instruction, otherwise it will point to freed memory. Similarly, when a fusion computation dies, we must clear the fusion instructions's called_computations_.

We also add a boolean field in HloComputation to determine if it is a fusion computation, since with this CL we can have (unreachable) fusion computations whose fusion instruction is null.

Last, do a nullptr check during module cloning, to avoid runtime errors due to unreachable computations.

Previously, when using custom kernel creators the function library runtime being
passed to the custom `CreateKernel` call was the wrong one (different from
other `CreateKernel` call) which led to missing func def's in following
scenario:
1) Custom kernel creator is used.
2) `FunctionLibraryRuntimeImpl::CreateKernel` is called directly from
   `FunctionLibraryRuntimeImpl::CreateItem`.
3) The `item` uses a function library runtime overlay which contains func def's
   that are missing from `this`.

StructuredCoder is the only thing that decodes the input signatures from the SavedModel concrete functions, and Keras uses it to build the layers loaded from config. The layers must be built before loading the other functions/objects from the SavedModel in order to prevent them from creating new sublayers (which would not have the correct weights). Thus, we can't remove the use of StructuredCoder from Keras right now.

Change-Id: I0cd72666013e9b8696aa26052ca6fde57e15f8fc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/waterdrops/tensorflow/commits/d7d893b1af5307d2fe196a8796216ffb81578287"},{"sha":"b31c2073f058ee979e2085473ffff274f82eeefd","author":{"name":"Dimitris Vardoulakis","email":"532a0f5dcb324b87a62941a290161c72e1fa9537@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:HLO] Cleanly destruct fusion instructions and their computations.

If a fusion instruction dies before its computation, the computation becomes unreachable, but it may not be destructed until later. In this case, we need to clear its back-pointer to the fusion instruction, otherwise it will point to freed memory. Similarly, when a fusion computation dies, we must clear the fusion instructions's called_computations_.

We also add a boolean field in HloComputation to determine if it is a fusion computation, since with this CL we can have (unreachable) fusion computations whose fusion instruction is null.

Last, do a nullptr check during module cloning, to avoid runtime errors due to unreachable computations.

* The exported '<React.StrictMode>' tag remains the same and opts legacy subtrees into strict mode level one ('mode == StrictModeL1'). This mode enables DEV-only double rendering, double component lifecycles, string ref warnings, legacy context warnings, etc. The primary purpose of this mode is to help detected render phase side effects. No new behavior. Roots created with experimental 'createRoot' and 'createBlockingRoot' APIs will also (for now) continue to default to strict mode level 1.

In a subsequent commit I will add support for a 'level' attribute on the '<React.StrictMode>' tag (as well as a new option supported by ). This will be the way to opt into strict mode level 2 ('mode == StrictModeL2'). This mode will enable DEV-only double invoking of effects on initial mount. This will simulate future Offscreen API semantics for trees being mounted, then hidden, and then shown again. The primary purpose of this mode is to enable applications to prepare for compatibility with the new Offscreen API (more information to follow shortly).

For now, this commit changes no public facing behavior. The only mechanism for opting into strict mode level 2 is the pre-existing 'enableDoubleInvokingEffects' feature flag (only enabled within Facebook for now).

* Renamed strict mode constants

StrictModeL1 -> StrictLegacyMode and StrictModeL2 -> StrictEffectsMode

* Renamed tests

* Split strict effects mode into two flags

One flag ('enableStrictEffects') enables strict mode level 2. It is similar to 'debugRenderPhaseSideEffectsForStrictMode' which enables srtict mode level 1.

The second flag ('createRootStrictEffectsByDefault') controls the default strict mode level for 'createRoot' trees. For now, all 'createRoot' trees remain level 1 by default. We will experiment with level 2 within Facebook.

This is a prerequisite for adding a configurable option to 'createRoot' that enables choosing a different StrictMode level than the default.

* Add StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop and createRoot 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option

New StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop allows specifying which level of strict mode to use. If no level attribute is specified, StrictLegacyMode will be used to maintain backwards compatibility. Otherwise the following is true:
* Level 0 does nothing
* Level 1 selects StrictLegacyMode
* Level 2 selects StrictEffectsMode (which includes StrictLegacyMode)

Levels can be increased with nesting (0 -> 1 -> 2) but not decreased.

This commit also adds a new 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option to the createRoot and createBatchedRoot APIs. This option can be used to override default behavior to increase or decrease the StrictMode level of the root.

* Move context comparison to consumer

In the lazy context implementation, not all context changes are
propagated from the provider, so we can't rely on the propagation alone
to mark the consumer as dirty. The consumer needs to compare to the
previous value, like we do for state and context.

I added a `memoizedValue` field to the context dependency type. Then in
the consumer, we iterate over the current dependencies to see if
something changed. We only do this iteration after props and state has
already bailed out, so it's a relatively uncommon path, except at the
root of a changed subtree. Alternatively, we could move these
comparisons into `readContext`, but that's a much hotter path, so I
think this is an appropriate trade off.

* [Experiment] Lazily propagate context changes

When a context provider changes, we scan the tree for matching consumers
and mark them as dirty so that we know they have pending work. This
prevents us from bailing out if, say, an intermediate wrapper is
memoized.

Currently, we propagate these changes eagerly, at the provider.

However, in many cases, we would have ended up visiting the consumer
nodes anyway, as part of the normal render traversal, because there's no
memoized node in between that bails out.

We can save CPU cycles by propagating changes only when we hit a
memoized component — so, instead of propagating eagerly at the provider,
we propagate lazily if or when something bails out.

Most of our bailout logic is centralized in
`bailoutOnAlreadyFinishedWork`, so this ended up being not that
difficult to implement correctly.

There are some exceptions: Suspense and Offscreen. Those are special
because they sometimes defer the rendering of their children to a
completely separate render cycle. In those cases, we must take extra
care to propagate *all* the context changes, not just the first one.

I'm pleasantly surprised at how little I needed to change in this
initial implementation. I was worried I'd have to use the reconciler
fork, but I ended up being able to wrap all my changes in a regular
feature flag. So, we could run an experiment in parallel to our other
ones.

I do consider this a risky rollout overall because of the potential for
subtle semantic deviations. However, the model is simple enough that I
don't expect us to have trouble fixing regressions if or when they arise
during internal dogfooding.

---

This is largely based on [RFC#118](https://github.com/reactjs/rfcs/pull/118),
by @gnoff. I did deviate in some of the implementation details, though.

The main one is how I chose to track context changes. Instead of storing
a dirty flag on the stack, I added a `memoizedValue` field to the
context dependency object. Then, to check if something has changed, the
consumer compares the new context value to the old (memoized) one.

This is necessary because of Suspense and Offscreen — those components
defer work from one render into a later one. When the subtree continues
rendering, the stack from the previous render is no longer available.
But the memoized values on the dependencies list are. This requires a
bit more work when a consumer bails out, but nothing considerable, and
there are ways we could optimize it even further. Conceptually, this
model is really appealing, since it matches how our other features
"reactively" detect changes — `useMemo`, `useEffect`,
`getDerivedStateFromProps`, the built-in cache, and so on.

I also intentionally dropped support for
`unstable_calculateChangedBits`. We're planning to remove this API
anyway before the next major release, in favor of context selectors.
It's an unstable feature that we never advertised; I don't think it's
seen much adoption.

Co-Authored-By: Josh Story <jcs.gnoff@gmail.com>

* Propagate all contexts in single pass

Instead of propagating the tree once per changed context, we can check
all the contexts in a single propagation. This inverts the two loops so
that the faster loop (O(numberOfContexts)) is inside the more expensive
loop (O(numberOfFibers * avgContextDepsPerFiber)).

This adds a bit of overhead to the case where only a single context
changes because you have to unwrap the context from the array. I'm also
unsure if this will hurt cache locality.

Co-Authored-By: Josh Story <jcs.gnoff@gmail.com>

* Stop propagating at nearest dependency match

Because we now propagate all context providers in a single traversal, we
can defer context propagation to a subtree without losing information
about which context providers we're deferring — it's all of them.

Theoretically, this is a big optimization because it means we'll never
propagate to any tree that has work scheduled on it, nor will we ever
propagate the same tree twice.

There's an awkward case related to bailing out of the siblings of a
context consumer. Because those siblings don't bail out until after
they've already entered the begin phase, we have to do extra work to
make sure they don't unecessarily propagate context again. We could
avoid this by adding an earlier bailout for sibling nodes, something
we've discussed in the past. We should consider this during the next
refactor of the fiber tree structure.

Co-Authored-By: Josh Story <jcs.gnoff@gmail.com>

* Mark trees that need propagation in readContext

Instead of storing matched context consumers in a Set, we can mark
when a consumer receives an update inside `readContext`.

I hesistated to put anything in this function because it's such a hot
path, but so are bail outs. Fortunately, we only need to set this flag
once, the first time a context is read. So I think it's a reasonable
trade off.

In exchange, propagation is faster because we no longer need to
accumulate a Set of matched consumers, and fiber bailouts are faster
because we don't need to consult that Set. And the code is simpler.

Co-authored-by: Josh Story <jcs.gnoff@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ludehsar/react/commits/c7b4497988e81606f1c7686434f55a49342c9efc"},{"sha":"f04bcb8139cfa341640ea875c2eae15523ae9cd9","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"[Bugfix] Reset `subtreeFlags` in `resetWorkInProgress` (#20948)

[{"sha":"11ef8d3ba983d6fb0b1597e715bf45e3b882a507","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"overlay2: support "userxattr" option (kernel 5.11)

The "userxattr" option is needed for mounting overlayfs inside a user namespace with kernel >= 5.11.

The "userxattr" option is NOT needed for the initial user namespace (aka "the host").

Also, Ubuntu (since circa 2015) and Debian (since 10) with kernel < 5.11 can mount the overlayfs in a user namespace without the "userxattr" option.

The corresponding kernel commit: 2d2f2d7322ff43e0fe92bf8cccdc0b09449bf2e1
> **ovl: user xattr**
>
> Optionally allow using "user.overlay." namespace instead of "trusted.overlay."
> ...
> Disable redirect_dir and metacopy options, because these would allow privilege escalation through direct manipulation of the
> "user.overlay.redirect" or "user.overlay.metacopy" xattrs.

Fix issue 42055

Related to containerd/containerd PR 5076

This seems to be testing a strange case, specifically that one can set
the `--net` and `--network` in the same command with the same network.

Indeed this used to work with older CLIs but newer ones error out when
validating the request before sending it to the daemon.

Opening this for discussion because:

1. This doesn't seem to be testing anything at all related to the rest
   of the test
2. Not really providing any value here.
3. Is testing that a technically invalid option is successful (whether
   the option should be valid as it relates to the CLI accepting it is
   debatable).
4. Such a case seems fringe and even a bug in whatever is calling the
   CLI with such options.

The "userxattr" option is needed for mounting overlayfs inside a user namespace with kernel >= 5.11.

The "userxattr" option is NOT needed for the initial user namespace (aka "the host").

Also, Ubuntu (since circa 2015) and Debian (since 10) with kernel < 5.11 can mount the overlayfs in a user namespace without the "userxattr" option.

The corresponding kernel commit: 2d2f2d7322ff43e0fe92bf8cccdc0b09449bf2e1
> **ovl: user xattr**
>
> Optionally allow using "user.overlay." namespace instead of "trusted.overlay."
> ...
> Disable redirect_dir and metacopy options, because these would allow privilege escalation through direct manipulation of the
> "user.overlay.redirect" or "user.overlay.metacopy" xattrs.

Fix issue 42055

Related to containerd/containerd PR 5076

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/phiberoptick/moby/commits/4be98a38e7810940c260d778cfe128b97d9245fb"},{"sha":"e31086320ea0305e2cc70490160ee30480471680","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Remove cli test for duplicate --net/--network opts

This seems to be testing a strange case, specifically that one can set
the `--net` and `--network` in the same command with the same network.

Indeed this used to work with older CLIs but newer ones error out when
validating the request before sending it to the daemon.

Opening this for discussion because:

1. This doesn't seem to be testing anything at all related to the rest
   of the test
2. Not really providing any value here.
3. Is testing that a technically invalid option is successful (whether
   the option should be valid as it relates to the CLI accepting it is
   debatable).
4. Such a case seems fringe and even a bug in whatever is calling the
   CLI with such options.

Remove cli test for duplicate --net/--network opts","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/phiberoptick/moby/commits/e0c87f90cd93fbbfe1ba0e0abc80ba757e3b0a82"},{"sha":"5a664dc87d79ddc9f09c7a963c52f491999dc939","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"jsonfile: more defensive reader implementation

Tonis mentioned that we can run into issues if there is more error
handling added here. This adds a custom reader implementation which is
like io.MultiReader except it does not cache EOF's.
What got us into trouble in the first place is `io.MultiReader` will
always return EOF once it has received an EOF, however the error
handling that we are going for is to recover from an EOF because the
underlying file is a file which can have more data added to it after
EOF.

[{"sha":"4be98a38e7810940c260d778cfe128b97d9245fb","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix handling for json-file io.UnexpectedEOF

When the multireader hits EOF, we will always get EOF from it, so we
cannot store the multrireader fro later error handling, only for the
decoder.

Thanks @tobiasstadler for pointing this error out.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/meunice/moby/commits/4be98a38e7810940c260d778cfe128b97d9245fb"},{"sha":"5a664dc87d79ddc9f09c7a963c52f491999dc939","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"jsonfile: more defensive reader implementation

Tonis mentioned that we can run into issues if there is more error
handling added here. This adds a custom reader implementation which is
like io.MultiReader except it does not cache EOF's.
What got us into trouble in the first place is `io.MultiReader` will
always return EOF once it has received an EOF, however the error
handling that we are going for is to recover from an EOF because the
underlying file is a file which can have more data added to it after
EOF.

[{"sha":"d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605","author":{"name":"Rémi Lapeyre","email":"953e8a3102147c156e7cfddb2d9937b841ad931f@lenstra.fr"},"message":"Use a global sequence to create the IDs for each workspace

Until now the default workspace for every project would have the ID 1,
which would make it impossible to lock them at the same time since we
use the ID to identify the lock. With a global sequence to generate the
IDs, the default workspace will now have a different ID for each project
and it will be possible to lock multiple unrelated projects at the same
time.

If an old version of Terraform tries to get the lock on a project created
with this new version it will work as we continue to use the ID of the
workspace, we just change the way we generate them.

If this version tries to get a lock on a project created by an old
version of Terraform it will work as usual, but we may encounter a
conflict with another unrelated project. This is already the current
behavior so it's not an issue to persist this behavior. As users migrate
to an up-to-date version of Terraform this will stop.

Projects already present in the database will keep their conflicting IDs,
I did not wanted to change them as users may be reading the states
directly in the database for some reason. They can if they want change
them manually to remove conflicts, newly created projects will work
without manual intervention.

Closes https://github.com/hashicorp/terraform/issues/22833","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/edgarsandi/terraform/commits/d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605"},{"sha":"3c6b2a8780ad090670f36754cf468817f701b25a","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"rename attachDataResourceDependsOnTransformer

Fixes #27506

Add a new flag `-lockfile=readonly` to `terraform init`.
It would be useful to allow us to suppress dependency lockfile changes
explicitly.

The type of the `-lockfile` flag is string rather than bool, leaving
room for future extensions to other behavior variants.

The readonly mode suppresses lockfile changes, but should verify
checksums against the information already recorded. It should conflict
with the `-upgrade` flag.

Note: In the original use-case described in #27506, I would like to
suppress adding zh hashes, but a test code here suppresses adding h1
hashes because it's easy for testing.

This commit adds a comprehensive JSON format for diagnostics, which
ensures that all current diagnostic output can be semantically
represented in a machine-readable format. The diagnostic formatter
interface remains unchanged, but it first transforms its input via the
JSON format to ensure that there is only one code path for creating the
diagnostic data.

The JSON diagnostic renderer extracts the non-presentational logic from
the format package, and returns a structure which can either be
marshaled into JSON or rendered as text. The resulting text diagnostic
output is unchanged for all cases covered by unit tests and my own
manual testing.

Included in this commit are a number of golden reference files for the
marshaled JSON output of a diagnostic. This format should change rarely
if at all, and these are in place to ensure that any changes to the
format are intentional and considered.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/edgarsandi/terraform/commits/d9d88b92439b9047570bcfa5fc1e90cf71aec60d"}]

* Move context comparison to consumer

In the lazy context implementation, not all context changes are
propagated from the provider, so we can't rely on the propagation alone
to mark the consumer as dirty. The consumer needs to compare to the
previous value, like we do for state and context.

I added a `memoizedValue` field to the context dependency type. Then in
the consumer, we iterate over the current dependencies to see if
something changed. We only do this iteration after props and state has
already bailed out, so it's a relatively uncommon path, except at the
root of a changed subtree. Alternatively, we could move these
comparisons into `readContext`, but that's a much hotter path, so I
think this is an appropriate trade off.

* [Experiment] Lazily propagate context changes

When a context provider changes, we scan the tree for matching consumers
and mark them as dirty so that we know they have pending work. This
prevents us from bailing out if, say, an intermediate wrapper is
memoized.

Currently, we propagate these changes eagerly, at the provider.

However, in many cases, we would have ended up visiting the consumer
nodes anyway, as part of the normal render traversal, because there's no
memoized node in between that bails out.

We can save CPU cycles by propagating changes only when we hit a
memoized component — so, instead of propagating eagerly at the provider,
we propagate lazily if or when something bails out.

Most of our bailout logic is centralized in
`bailoutOnAlreadyFinishedWork`, so this ended up being not that
difficult to implement correctly.

There are some exceptions: Suspense and Offscreen. Those are special
because they sometimes defer the rendering of their children to a
completely separate render cycle. In those cases, we must take extra
care to propagate *all* the context changes, not just the first one.

I'm pleasantly surprised at how little I needed to change in this
initial implementation. I was worried I'd have to use the reconciler
fork, but I ended up being able to wrap all my changes in a regular
feature flag. So, we could run an experiment in parallel to our other
ones.

I do consider this a risky rollout overall because of the potential for
subtle semantic deviations. However, the model is simple enough that I
don't expect us to have trouble fixing regressions if or when they arise
during internal dogfooding.

---

This is largely based on [RFC#118](https://github.com/reactjs/rfcs/pull/118),
by @gnoff. I did deviate in some of the implementation details, though.

The main one is how I chose to track context changes. Instead of storing
a dirty flag on the stack, I added a `memoizedValue` field to the
context dependency object. Then, to check if something has changed, the
consumer compares the new context value to the old (memoized) one.

This is necessary because of Suspense and Offscreen — those components
defer work from one render into a later one. When the subtree continues
rendering, the stack from the previous render is no longer available.
But the memoized values on the dependencies list are. This requires a
bit more work when a consumer bails out, but nothing considerable, and
there are ways we could optimize it even further. Conceptually, this
model is really appealing, since it matches how our other features
"reactively" detect changes — `useMemo`, `useEffect`,
`getDerivedStateFromProps`, the built-in cache, and so on.

I also intentionally dropped support for
`unstable_calculateChangedBits`. We're planning to remove this API
anyway before the next major release, in favor of context selectors.
It's an unstable feature that we never advertised; I don't think it's
seen much adoption.

Co-Authored-By: Josh Story <jcs.gnoff@gmail.com>

* Propagate all contexts in single pass

Instead of propagating the tree once per changed context, we can check
all the contexts in a single propagation. This inverts the two loops so
that the faster loop (O(numberOfContexts)) is inside the more expensive
loop (O(numberOfFibers * avgContextDepsPerFiber)).

This adds a bit of overhead to the case where only a single context
changes because you have to unwrap the context from the array. I'm also
unsure if this will hurt cache locality.

Co-Authored-By: Josh Story <jcs.gnoff@gmail.com>

* Stop propagating at nearest dependency match

Because we now propagate all context providers in a single traversal, we
can defer context propagation to a subtree without losing information
about which context providers we're deferring — it's all of them.

Theoretically, this is a big optimization because it means we'll never
propagate to any tree that has work scheduled on it, nor will we ever
propagate the same tree twice.

There's an awkward case related to bailing out of the siblings of a
context consumer. Because those siblings don't bail out until after
they've already entered the begin phase, we have to do extra work to
make sure they don't unecessarily propagate context again. We could
avoid this by adding an earlier bailout for sibling nodes, something
we've discussed in the past. We should consider this during the next
refactor of the fiber tree structure.

Co-Authored-By: Josh Story <jcs.gnoff@gmail.com>

* Mark trees that need propagation in readContext

Instead of storing matched context consumers in a Set, we can mark
when a consumer receives an update inside `readContext`.

I hesistated to put anything in this function because it's such a hot
path, but so are bail outs. Fortunately, we only need to set this flag
once, the first time a context is read. So I think it's a reasonable
trade off.

In exchange, propagation is faster because we no longer need to
accumulate a Set of matched consumers, and fiber bailouts are faster
because we don't need to consult that Set. And the code is simpler.

  vectorized types, but it is not actually needed: the use of 'const
  __restrict__' means the kernel still generates LDG instructions

    skip until threshold is reached. This makes it symmetrical to
    subsequent compilations of the cluster.
    2) bump the threshold for compilation to the third execution of
    the cluster.
    3) change megamorphic flagging to incldue compiel time. If a cluster
    ever takes more than 30 seconds to compile, mark it megamorphic so
    that it won't compile again

    1) add option to opt into asynchronous compilation
    2) asynchronous compilation uses a dedicated number of threads
    to start a cluster instance compilation while the fallback path
    is executed
    3) limit number of ongoing compilations to a fixed threshold

[{"sha":"e79f204cc6c9762a2a6bec0cea549dd613ffc811","author":{"name":"A. Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Remove guards around b/143684500.

Several kernels have previously been disabled for std::complex due
to lack of operator support on device.  This is no longer the case,
and these kernels can now be enabled.

NOTE: we also needed to replace `a+=b` and `a-=b` with `a=a+b` and
`a=a-b` for use with `std::complex<T>` on device.  Unfortunately MSVC
does not stricly follow the c++ standard, and unnecessarily specializes
these operators. This prevents us from using Eigen's device-compatible
overrides.  Without these overrides, the original compound assignments
`+=` and `-=` silently fail on GPU.

[{"sha":"4be98a38e7810940c260d778cfe128b97d9245fb","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix handling for json-file io.UnexpectedEOF

When the multireader hits EOF, we will always get EOF from it, so we
cannot store the multrireader fro later error handling, only for the
decoder.

Thanks @tobiasstadler for pointing this error out.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/moby/commits/4be98a38e7810940c260d778cfe128b97d9245fb"},{"sha":"5a664dc87d79ddc9f09c7a963c52f491999dc939","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"jsonfile: more defensive reader implementation

Tonis mentioned that we can run into issues if there is more error
handling added here. This adds a custom reader implementation which is
like io.MultiReader except it does not cache EOF's.
What got us into trouble in the first place is `io.MultiReader` will
always return EOF once it has received an EOF, however the error
handling that we are going for is to recover from an EOF because the
underlying file is a file which can have more data added to it after
EOF.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/moby/commits/5a664dc87d79ddc9f09c7a963c52f491999dc939"},{"sha":"788f2883d285fc997d25cd27235c5b17cf3c0947","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"4876a66208932b3750ccc18b302877b042a311b1@hey.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #42104 from cpuguy83/41820_fix_json_unexpected_eof","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/moby/commits/788f2883d285fc997d25cd27235c5b17cf3c0947"}]

DevTools has a feature to force a Suspense boundary to show a fallback.
This feature causes us to skip the first render pass (where we render
the primary children) and go straight to rendering the fallback.

There's a Legacy Mode-only codepath that failed to take this scenario
into account, instead assuming that whenever a fallback is being
rendered, it was preceded by an attempt to render the primary children.

SuspenseList can also cause us to skip the first pass, but the relevant
branch is Legacy Mode-only, and SuspenseList is not supported in
Legacy Mode.

Fixes a test that I had temporarily disabled when upstreaming the Lanes
implementation in #19108.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/majacQ/react/commits/6ba25b96df5d4179bf8aba3c3fe1ace3dce28234"},{"sha":"5b98656909d46fff6da135a8e60ffdc529e432f5","author":{"name":"Jack Works","email":"d91f74da464f2fb54aabfad6104262999369b274@protonmail.com"},"message":"fix: use define property to overwrite console, close #19099 (#19123)

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rizalgowandy/moby/commits/80cc1f1d6fb1d03014f7ef5d3a1e216538ddb855"},{"sha":"11ef8d3ba983d6fb0b1597e715bf45e3b882a507","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"overlay2: support "userxattr" option (kernel 5.11)

The "userxattr" option is needed for mounting overlayfs inside a user namespace with kernel >= 5.11.

The "userxattr" option is NOT needed for the initial user namespace (aka "the host").

Also, Ubuntu (since circa 2015) and Debian (since 10) with kernel < 5.11 can mount the overlayfs in a user namespace without the "userxattr" option.

The corresponding kernel commit: 2d2f2d7322ff43e0fe92bf8cccdc0b09449bf2e1
> **ovl: user xattr**
>
> Optionally allow using "user.overlay." namespace instead of "trusted.overlay."
> ...
> Disable redirect_dir and metacopy options, because these would allow privilege escalation through direct manipulation of the
> "user.overlay.redirect" or "user.overlay.metacopy" xattrs.

Fix issue 42055

Related to containerd/containerd PR 5076

This seems to be testing a strange case, specifically that one can set
the `--net` and `--network` in the same command with the same network.

Indeed this used to work with older CLIs but newer ones error out when
validating the request before sending it to the daemon.

Opening this for discussion because:

1. This doesn't seem to be testing anything at all related to the rest
   of the test
2. Not really providing any value here.
3. Is testing that a technically invalid option is successful (whether
   the option should be valid as it relates to the CLI accepting it is
   debatable).
4. Such a case seems fringe and even a bug in whatever is calling the
   CLI with such options.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/dgkh1975/moby/commits/80cc1f1d6fb1d03014f7ef5d3a1e216538ddb855"},{"sha":"11ef8d3ba983d6fb0b1597e715bf45e3b882a507","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"overlay2: support "userxattr" option (kernel 5.11)

The "userxattr" option is needed for mounting overlayfs inside a user namespace with kernel >= 5.11.

The "userxattr" option is NOT needed for the initial user namespace (aka "the host").

Also, Ubuntu (since circa 2015) and Debian (since 10) with kernel < 5.11 can mount the overlayfs in a user namespace without the "userxattr" option.

The corresponding kernel commit: 2d2f2d7322ff43e0fe92bf8cccdc0b09449bf2e1
> **ovl: user xattr**
>
> Optionally allow using "user.overlay." namespace instead of "trusted.overlay."
> ...
> Disable redirect_dir and metacopy options, because these would allow privilege escalation through direct manipulation of the
> "user.overlay.redirect" or "user.overlay.metacopy" xattrs.

Fix issue 42055

Related to containerd/containerd PR 5076

This seems to be testing a strange case, specifically that one can set
the `--net` and `--network` in the same command with the same network.

Indeed this used to work with older CLIs but newer ones error out when
validating the request before sending it to the daemon.

Opening this for discussion because:

1. This doesn't seem to be testing anything at all related to the rest
   of the test
2. Not really providing any value here.
3. Is testing that a technically invalid option is successful (whether
   the option should be valid as it relates to the CLI accepting it is
   debatable).
4. Such a case seems fringe and even a bug in whatever is calling the
   CLI with such options.

[{"sha":"cf485e6f6b4d6a6e2ccfe7a12537941925316e86","author":{"name":"Sebastian Markbåge","email":"8a279ae1320350359ecfec7a379763633f1edc4c@fb.com"},"message":"[Fizz] Expose a method to abort a pending request (#21027)

* Track all suspended work while it's still pending

This allows us to abort work and put everything into client rendered mode
if we don't want to wait for further I/O.

It also allows us to cancel fallbacks if we complete the main content

  vectorized types, but it is not actually needed: the use of 'const

The "userxattr" option is needed for mounting overlayfs inside a user namespace with kernel >= 5.11.

The "userxattr" option is NOT needed for the initial user namespace (aka "the host").

Also, Ubuntu (since circa 2015) and Debian (since 10) with kernel < 5.11 can mount the overlayfs in a user namespace without the "userxattr" option.

The corresponding kernel commit: 2d2f2d7322ff43e0fe92bf8cccdc0b09449bf2e1
> **ovl: user xattr**
>
> Optionally allow using "user.overlay." namespace instead of "trusted.overlay."
> ...
> Disable redirect_dir and metacopy options, because these would allow privilege escalation through direct manipulation of the
> "user.overlay.redirect" or "user.overlay.metacopy" xattrs.

Fix issue 42055

This seems to be testing a strange case, specifically that one can set
the `--net` and `--network` in the same command with the same network.

Indeed this used to work with older CLIs but newer ones error out when
validating the request before sending it to the daemon.

Opening this for discussion because:

1. This doesn't seem to be testing anything at all related to the rest
   of the test
2. Not really providing any value here.
3. Is testing that a technically invalid option is successful (whether
   the option should be valid as it relates to the CLI accepting it is
   debatable).
4. Such a case seems fringe and even a bug in whatever is calling the
   CLI with such options.

[{"sha":"4be98a38e7810940c260d778cfe128b97d9245fb","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix handling for json-file io.UnexpectedEOF

When the multireader hits EOF, we will always get EOF from it, so we
cannot store the multrireader fro later error handling, only for the
decoder.

Thanks @tobiasstadler for pointing this error out.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/moby/moby/commits/4be98a38e7810940c260d778cfe128b97d9245fb"},{"sha":"5a664dc87d79ddc9f09c7a963c52f491999dc939","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"jsonfile: more defensive reader implementation

Tonis mentioned that we can run into issues if there is more error
handling added here. This adds a custom reader implementation which is
like io.MultiReader except it does not cache EOF's.
What got us into trouble in the first place is `io.MultiReader` will
always return EOF once it has received an EOF, however the error
handling that we are going for is to recover from an EOF because the
underlying file is a file which can have more data added to it after
EOF.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/moby/moby/commits/5a664dc87d79ddc9f09c7a963c52f491999dc939"},{"sha":"788f2883d285fc997d25cd27235c5b17cf3c0947","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"4876a66208932b3750ccc18b302877b042a311b1@hey.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #42104 from cpuguy83/41820_fix_json_unexpected_eof","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/moby/moby/commits/788f2883d285fc997d25cd27235c5b17cf3c0947"}]

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/moby/commits/80cc1f1d6fb1d03014f7ef5d3a1e216538ddb855"},{"sha":"11ef8d3ba983d6fb0b1597e715bf45e3b882a507","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"overlay2: support "userxattr" option (kernel 5.11)

The "userxattr" option is needed for mounting overlayfs inside a user namespace with kernel >= 5.11.

The "userxattr" option is NOT needed for the initial user namespace (aka "the host").

Also, Ubuntu (since circa 2015) and Debian (since 10) with kernel < 5.11 can mount the overlayfs in a user namespace without the "userxattr" option.

The corresponding kernel commit: 2d2f2d7322ff43e0fe92bf8cccdc0b09449bf2e1
> **ovl: user xattr**
>
> Optionally allow using "user.overlay." namespace instead of "trusted.overlay."
> ...
> Disable redirect_dir and metacopy options, because these would allow privilege escalation through direct manipulation of the
> "user.overlay.redirect" or "user.overlay.metacopy" xattrs.

Fix issue 42055

Related to containerd/containerd PR 5076

This seems to be testing a strange case, specifically that one can set
the `--net` and `--network` in the same command with the same network.

Indeed this used to work with older CLIs but newer ones error out when
validating the request before sending it to the daemon.

Opening this for discussion because:

1. This doesn't seem to be testing anything at all related to the rest
   of the test
2. Not really providing any value here.
3. Is testing that a technically invalid option is successful (whether
   the option should be valid as it relates to the CLI accepting it is
   debatable).
4. Such a case seems fringe and even a bug in whatever is calling the
   CLI with such options.
